                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Fixes to this should be done with content, not by changing the way a spell works. 
<br />

<br />
No one would ever use a charmed pet to kill chromodrags in skyfire. Why? It's obvious. They constantly proc a dispell. 
<br />

<br />
Lower level enchanters typically don't solo using "giants" as charmed pets. Why? Those guys are immune to mez and stun, making it more difficult. 
<br />

<br />
Charm wasn't "overpowered" in kunark. That's because mob dps didn't so outrageously dwarf that of any player character. 
<br />

<br />
Sony has been going about "fixing" charm in <span style="font-weight: bold">all</span> the wrong ways. There are dozens and dozens of ideas proposed by enchanters that would make charming less of a balance issue without removing or diminishing charm's capabilities wholey. 
<br />

<br />
Like what? I'm sure devs have read many of the suggestions. I'm baffled that they haven't even dabbled with anything enchanters have suggested. Give "regular" mobs that are fully charmable but unsnarable (that don't run when low on health). Put a 1% slow component to charm. Add mobs that proc dispell. Or, mobs that proc a 0 duration root to remove any current root. Instead of just increasing mob dps as a "challenge", why not try mobs that hit for half as much, have half the hp, but come in swarms and are impossible to "single" pull? Make a mob challenging my tweaking the AI so that it only responds to certain types of aggro... like healing spell aggro only, or that can be rooted but ignore conventional root aggro rules (proximity). Mobs that come in swarms that have, say, a reduced modifier for spell aggro would be a unique yet challenging change, as you can throw a dozen at one group, have each individual mob do pathetic dps per mob, and warrios would love it (if they don't stun the poor fellow) 
<br />

<br />
Sony has been in the "rut" if 1 group vs one mob for the purposes of balance between PoP and GoD. So, they tried to make the game challenging off of that basis. 
<br />

<br />
When a zone is challenging beause of the mobs' "dps", then charm will be overpowering. 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">If content is challenging for reasons other than damage output of a single mob, charm will not be overpowered</span></span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
